"Wei T.-Y., Lu S.-Y., Chang Y.-C.","A new class of opacified monolithic aerogels of ultralow high-temperature thermal conductivities",2009,"Journal of Physical Chemistry C","113","17",,"7424","7428",,,10.1021/jp900380q,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-67049086507&partnerID=40&md5=be80f10bbceba07a5e2619fd4d76e1e0","Department of Chemical Engineering, National Tsing-Hua University, HsinChu, 30013, Taiwan; Industrial Energy-Saving Technology Division, Energy and Environment Laboratories, Industrial Technology Research Institute, HsinChu, 310, Taiwan","Wei, T.-Y., Department of Chemical Engineering, National Tsing-Hua University, HsinChu, 30013, Taiwan; Lu, S.-Y., Department of Chemical Engineering, National Tsing-Hua University, HsinChu, 30013, Taiwan; Chang, Y.-C., Industrial Energy-Saving Technology Division, Energy and Environment Laboratories, Industrial Technology Research Institute, HsinChu, 310, Taiwan","The development of materials of ultralow high-temperature thermal conductivities for applications in hightemperature thermal insulations has become increasingly more important than ever in view of the ever worsening issues of fossil energy depletion and global warming that call for more demanding energy-saving practices. In this study, a new class of opacified monolithic aerogels of ultralow high-temperature thermal conductivities was developed for thermal insulation applications at high temperatures. Carbon nanofibers were successfully incorporated into the mesoporous network of silica aerogels at concentrations as high as 20 wt % through an accelerated-gelation sol-gel process to enhance the dimensional stability of the silica aerogels and to suppress the thermal radiations that become dominant at high temperatures, to achieve an ultralow thermal conductivity of 0.050 W/m-K at 500 °C, whereas maintaining a thermal stability above 500 °C (much better than the conventional high-temperature thermal insulation materials: 0.3 W/m-K at 500 °C for glass fibers, 0.1 W/m-K at 527 °C for alumina fused brick, and 1.7 W/m-K at 527 °C for sillimante). © 2009 American Chemical Society.",,"A-thermal; Energy saving; Fossil energy; High temperature; Insulation applications; Mesoporous network; Monolithic aerogels; New class; Silica aerogels; Thermal insulation materials; Thermal radiations; Aerogels; Alumina; Carbon fiber reinforced plastics; Carbon fibers; Carbon nanofibers; Ceramic materials; Coagulation; Dimensional stability; Energy conservation; Fused silica; Gelation; Glass fibers; Global warming; Mesoporous materials; Silica; Silica gel; Sol-gel process; Thermal conductivity; Thermal insulation",,,,,,"Kistler, S.S., (1931) Nature (London), 227, p. 741; Hüsing, N., Schubert, U., (1998) Angew. Chem., Int. Ed, 37, p. 22; Pierre, A.C., Pajonk, G.M., (2002) Chem. Rev, 102, p. 4243; Frick, J., (1985) Proc. Phys, 6, p. 100; Schwertfeger, F., Schubert, U., (1995) Chem. Mater, 7, p. 1909; Lu, X., Arduini-Schuster, M.C., Kuhn, J., Nilsson, O., Frick, J., Pekala, R.W., (1992) Science, 255, p. 971; Hrubesh, L.W., Pekala, R.W., (1994) J. Mater. Res, 9, p. 731; Wang, J., Kuhn, J., Lu, X., (1995) J. Non-Cryst. Solids, 186, p. 296; Kuhn, J., Gleissner, T., Arduini-Schuster, M.C., Korder, S., Frick, J., (1995) J. Non-Cryst. Solids, 186, p. 291; Zeng, S.Q., Hunt, A., Greif, R., (1995) J. Non-Cryst. Solids, 186, p. 271; Kwon, Y.G., Choi, S.Y., Kang, E.S., Baek, S.S., (2000) J. Mater. Sci, 35, p. 6075; Wulf, R., Barth, G., Gross, U., (2007) Int. J. Thermophys, 28, p. 1679; Al-Ajlan, S.A., (2006) Appl. Thermal Eng, 26, p. 2184; (2009), www.osti.gov/bridge/product.biblio.jsp?query-id=0&page=0&osti-id=885664, MarchJeong, A.Y., Koo, S.M., Kim, D.P., (2000) J. Sol-Gel Sci. Technol, 19, p. 483; Sing, K.S.W., (1982) Pure Appl. Chem, 54, p. 2201; Brinker, C.J., Scherer, G.W., (1990) Sol-Gel Sci, p. 557; Wei, T.Y., Chang, T.F., Lu, S.Y., Chang, Y.C., (2003) J. Am. Ceram. Soc, 2007, p. 90; Wei, T.Y., Lu, S.Y., Chang, Y.C., (2007) J. Chin. Inst. Chem. Eng, 38, p. 477; Wei, T.Y., Kuo, C.Y., Hsu, Y.J., Lu, S.Y., Chang, Y.C., (2008) Microporous Mesoporous Mater, 112, p. 580; Wei, T.Y., Lu, S.Y., Chang, Y.C., (2008) J. Phys. Chem. B, 112, p. 11881","Lu, S.-Y.; Department of Chemical Engineering, National Tsing-Hua University, HsinChu, 30013, Taiwan; email: sylu@mx.nthu.edu.tw",,,,,,,,19327447,,,,"English","J. Phys. Chem. C",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-67049086507
